The assessment of β -convergence requires the analysis of the dynamics of DMUs located on the BPF and the worst practice frontier (WPF) between two consecutive extents of time. That process may arise because of the:
- Decline of the BPF coupled with the improvement, constancy, or decline at a smaller rate of the WPF;
- Improvement at a smaller rate, constancy, or decline of the BPF coupled with the improvement of the WPF.

According to the UN, the SDG 3 has thirteen targets, corresponding to nine ‘Outcome’ targets and four ‘Means of Implementation’ targets [43], whose individual attainment can be measured by one to five indicators. These health statistics were provided by WHO’s Global Health Observatory (GHO) database at https://www.who.int/gho/publications/world_health_statistics/en/, based on its annual ‘World Health Statistics’ reports issued between 2016 and 2020 (the ones that are SDG-related, unlike the previous 2005–2015 reports that concerned the Millennium Development Goals). From the initial twenty-six indicators, we did not consider:


- Two indicators that were left out of the GHO database (3.3.4 and 3.5.1);



- Seven indicators that had more than 25% of missing data in at least two years between 2016 and 2020 (3.3.1, 3.3.3, 3.7.1, 3.8.1, 3.8.2, 3.a.1, and 3.b.2).

Ultimately, eleven targets and seventeen indicators remained (see Tables 1
                         and 2
                        ), four of which being desirable and the remaining thirteen being undesirable.

Essentially, the policy implications that can be withdrawn from these results should rely on the fact that:


- Worldwide, most WHO Member States have not been able to close the gap between BPFs and WPFs between 2016 and 2020, given the decline of the WPF, although it occurred alongside an improvement at a lower rate of the BPF; this is the result of successful health and social policies and reforms targeted at the developed Member States, but, unfortunately, this was accompanied by the apparent decline of the health systems of the developing ones that may need increased national and international support towards the achievement of the UN’s SDG3 (see, e.g., Pereira et al. [52]);



- Some developing Member States have had significant progress in the same period, as is the case of those that belong to the Eastern Mediterranean Region, eventually due to the cooperation with developed Member States [47];



- The generalised decline of the BPF, detected both by the worldwide and regional benchmarking exercise, suggests that there is a need for improvement and, consequently, subsequent intervention in a vast number of developed Member States, especially those in the European Region. This may be explained by the higher burden that they have in guaranteeing the access to essential healthcare services in developing Member States while ensuring their own sustainability. There is a shortage of literature regarding the full advantages and disadvantages of international cooperation in the health sector [53], so this topic deserves further research.
